gulfed industry and risked undermining the rule of law. Warner explores the power dynamics, strategic errors and industrial battles that destroyed this attempt to tame trade unions and ultimately brought down a government, and that shape Conservative attitudes towards trade unions to this day.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLabor unionszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh  aDepoliticisation.  aEdward Heath.  aIn Place of Strife.  aIndustrial Relations Act 1971.  aIndustrial relations.  aMargaret Thatcher.  aMiners' strike.  aPoliticisation.  aStrikes.  aTrade unions.1 aWarner, Sam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152616602940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526166029423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526166029/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles